# Using Superpowers — Meta Skill
# Source: github.com/obra/superpowers | License: MIT

## When to Use
Always active as background priority system. Explicitly triggered on:
"what skills are available", "how do I use superpowers", "which skill applies here".

---

## Core Principle
**Invoke relevant or requested skills BEFORE any response or action.**
Even a 1% chance a skill applies requires invoking it before proceeding.

---

## Instruction Priority

1. User's explicit instructions (highest)
2. Superpowers skills (override defaults)
3. Default behavior (lowest)

When a skill and default behavior conflict — the skill wins.

---

## Invocation Order

1. **Process skills first** (shape how you work):
   - brainstorming (before implementation)
   - systematic-debugging (before fixes)
   - verification-before-completion (before claiming done)

2. **Implementation skills second** (do the work):
   - test-driven-development
   - subagent-driven-development
   - dispatching-parallel-agents

---

## Skill Map — Quick Reference

| Situation | Skill to invoke |
|-----------|----------------|
| Starting any new feature | brainstorming |
| Writing code | test-driven-development |
| Planning implementation | writing-plans |
| Executing a plan | subagent-driven-development |
| Multiple independent problems | dispatching-parallel-agents |
| Debugging an error | systematic-debugging |
| About to say "done" | verification-before-completion |
| Reviewing code | requesting-code-review |
| Receiving review feedback | receiving-code-review |
| New feature branch | using-git-worktrees |
| Work is complete | finishing-a-development-branch |
| Creating a new skill | writing-skills |

---

## Red Flags (Rationalization Indicators)

If you're thinking any of these, you're skipping a skill check:
- "This is just a simple question"
- "I need more context first"
- "Let me explore before using a skill"
- "This doesn't need a formal skill"
- "It's too quick for the full process"

Questions are tasks. Tasks need skill assessment.

---

## Skill Types

**Rigid skills** — follow exactly, no adaptation:
- test-driven-development
- systematic-debugging
- verification-before-completion

**Flexible skills** — apply principles contextually:
- brainstorming
- writing-plans
- requesting-code-review

---

